          "body": "Jeremiah 21:8-9 is one of the most counterintuitive survival commands in the Old Testament. 'I set before you the way of life and the way of death' echoes Moses's covenant appeal in Deuteronomy 30:15-19, but Moses was calling Israel into covenant faithfulness. Here, the covenant is broken beyond repair for the city, and the way of life is to defect to the besieging enemy. To remain in Jerusalem — loyal, patriotic, militarily resistant — is to die by the covenant curses of sword, famine, and plague. To go out and fall away to the Chaldeans is to live, with 'his own life as booty.' The phrase 'life as booty' is deliberately understated: not victory, not property, not honor — just life. Survival stripped of everything except breathing. This is the minimum. Peter Craigie (Word Biblical Commentary) notes that the Deuteronomic two-ways framework is radically recontextualized here: the way of life in Deuteronomy was Torah obedience; the way of life in Jeremiah 21 is obedience to the prophetic word that identifies Babylon as God's instrument. To resist Babylon is to resist God. To submit is to align with what God is doing, however painful that submission is."
