          "body": "The oracle to the house of David (21:11-14) is both a final appeal and an indictment. The command to 'administer justice every morning' (21:12) defines what Davidic kingship was always for. Psalm 72 provides the canonical portrait: the king defends the afflicted, delivers the needy, crushes the oppressor (Psalm 72:1-4, 12-14). The phrase 'every morning' is significant — it was the customary time for judicial proceedings in the ancient Near East; cases were heard at the city gate at dawn. The king who did justice every morning was doing what his office existed to do. The house of David had not done it. Their 'evil deeds' (21:12) — which chapters 22-23 elaborate in damning detail — include exploitation of the poor, shedding innocent blood, and building lavish palaces with forced labor (22:13-17). God's wrath, therefore, is not capricious; it burns 'with none to extinguish it' (21:12) precisely because it is the overflow of justice denied for decades. Calvin comments that God does not overlook the smallest injustice; when it accumulates without repentance, the fire becomes unquenchable."
