          "title": "The geography of pride — 'who will come down against us?'",
          "body": "The oracle's closing address to 'O valley dweller, O rocky plain' (21:13) targets a specific form of pride: geographic confidence. Jerusalem's location on a ridge above deep valleys — the Kidron to the east, Hinnom to the south and west — had historically made it militarily formidable. Jebusite defenders used similar arguments when David took the city (2 Samuel 5:6). The temple mount and palace complex rose above the surrounding terrain; the city felt impregnable to its inhabitants. The rhetorical question 'who will come down against us? Who will enter into our habitations?' (21:13) is not quoted to correct a mere military miscalculation — it is quoted to expose a spiritual presumption. The city had conflated its natural defenses with divine protection. If God lives here, who would dare attack? Jeremiah's answer is that the God who lives here has turned against the city precisely because it presumed on His presence while abandoning His demands. He will kindle a fire in the forest (21:14) — the cedar-rich palace complex (cf. 22:7) — and it will devour from within. The geography that generated the confidence will not resist the fire that God himself ignites."
