        "excerpt": "I Myself will war against you with an outstretched hand and a mighty arm, even in anger and wrath and great indignation.",
        "body": "The oracle Jeremiah delivers to Zedekiah's delegation is structured in two movements: first, the military inversion (vv. 4-5), then the sequential judgment (vv. 6-7). The military inversion in verse 4 is surgical: the weapons currently in Judah's hands, aimed outward at the Chaldeans, will be turned back and gathered into the city's center. God is not merely withdrawing support from Jerusalem's defenders; He is actively reversing the direction of their arms.\n\nVerse 5 contains the chapter's most theologically explosive claim. 'I Myself will war against you with an outstretched hand and a mighty arm' — the phrase *yad netuyah uzeroa chazaqah* is the standard Deuteronomic vocabulary for the Exodus: Deuteronomy 4:34 uses it for God's arm that delivered Israel from Egypt; Deuteronomy 26:8 uses it for the Passover-Exodus deliverance. Every Israelite who heard this phrase would have heard 'Exodus.' What Jeremiah does is attach that language to the opposite trajectory: the God who stretched out His arm to deliver Israel from Egypt now stretches out the same arm to deliver Jerusalem *to* Babylon. This is not poetic exaggeration; it is a precise theological claim that God's sovereign power is operating in the siege of Jerusalem just as purposefully as it operated in the plagues of Egypt — except now Israel is Egypt.\n\nThe emotional coloring of verse 5 — 'anger (*aph*), wrath (*chemah*), and great indignation (*qetseph gadol*)' — piles three synonyms for divine displeasure in ascending intensity. The three-fold accumulation mirrors the three-fold judgment instrument of verse 6 (man and beast dying of plague) and the three-fold instrument of verse 9 (sword, famine, pestilence). The triads reinforce one another: the divine anger is as comprehensive as the divine judgment.\n\nVerses 6-7 trace the sequence: plague first (striking all inhabitants, man and beast), then Nebuchadnezzar receives the survivors — Zedekiah, his servants, and the people — into his hand. The clause 'he will not spare them nor have pity nor compassion' (21:7) reverses the covenant language of Exodus 34:6 ('compassionate and gracious') not by denying God's character but by showing that God's own compassion has been exhausted and that He now commissions a Babylonian king to execute without mercy what Israel's persistent rebellion has merited.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yad netuyah uzeroa chazaqah* (outstretched hand and mighty arm, v.5) — Deuteronomy 4:34; 5:15; 26:8 use this exact phrase for Exodus deliverance. *Aph* (anger) + *chemah* (fury/wrath) + *qetseph gadol* (great indignation) — three ascending Hebrew terms for divine displeasure. *Racham* (compassion, v.7) shares a root with *rechem* (womb) — the most intimate, mother-like care. Its negation here signals total suspension of covenant tenderness."
