        "title": "Justice every morning — the dynasty's mandate, failure, and fire",
        "range": "21:11-14",
        "excerpt": "Administer justice every morning; and deliver the person who has been robbed from the power of his oppressor, that My wrath may not go forth like fire.",
        "body": "The chapter's third oracle addresses the house of David — the royal dynasty — and is the most theologically complex of the three. It begins with what sounds like a conditional appeal (vv. 11-12) and closes with what is in fact an unconditional announcement of judgment (vv. 13-14). The tension between them is the chapter's closing argument.\n\nThe summons to justice in verse 12 defines the Davidic mandate. 'Administer justice every morning' — *mishpat* (justice, equity, righteous judgment) administered at dawn, the customary hour for judicial proceedings at the city gate (cf. Amos 5:10-12, 15; 2 Samuel 15:2). The king's primary covenant function was to embody Yahweh's own justice in the social order, especially toward the vulnerable: the robbed person, the one crushed by the oppressor. Psalm 72 is the canonical portrait of this king: he defends the afflicted, saves the children of the needy, and crushes the oppressor (Psalm 72:4, 12-14). Isaiah 11:1-5 gives the eschatological version: the Branch of Jesse who 'will judge the poor with righteousness and decide with fairness for the afflicted of the earth.' The house of David had this function and had systematically failed it — chapters 22-23 will provide the specific indictments (22:3, 13-17; 23:5).\n\nThe fire language of verse 12 is not a new threat but the announcement of what has already been set in motion by the dynasty's failures. God's wrath burns 'like fire' with 'none to extinguish it' — a phrase that echoes Amos 5:6 (where Yahweh threatens to break out on Bethel 'like a fire, with none to quench it') and prepares for the closing image of verse 14. The unquenchable fire is the natural consequence of justice perpetually withheld.\n\nVerses 13-14 close the oracle by dismantling Jerusalem's geographic confidence. The city's inhabitants boast: 'Who will come down against us? Who will enter into our habitations?' (21:13). The question is not merely military; it is theological presumption — we are God's city, God's temple is here, who would dare? God answers in verse 14 with a counter-announcement: 'I will punish you according to the results of your deeds.' The punishment is proportionate (*peri maaleleykem* — 'the fruit of your deeds,' the harvest that your own actions have grown). And God will kindle the fire *in the forest* — the palace complex with its cedar paneling (cf. 22:7, 14-15; 1 Kings 7:2-3 where Solomon's palace is 'the house of the forest of Lebanon'). The image is complete: the proud cedar-house of the dynasty, which should have sheltered the justice of Yahweh, becomes the forest God Himself sets ablaze.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mishpat* (justice, v.12) — the comprehensive Old Testament term for righteous judicial ordering of society; its root (*shaphat*, to judge) underlies the whole covenant concept of royal function. *Chemah* (wrath, v.12) — the same word as in v.5's triple-anger construction; God's wrath is continuous from the military oracle to the royal one. *Paqad* (punish, v.14) — the covenant term for God's official visitation in judgment; cognate to *pequddah* (appointment, punishment). *Yaar* (forest, v.14) — almost certainly a reference to the palace's cedar construction (cf. 22:7, 14; 1 Kings 7:2)."
